			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">You probably should have posted this in the newbie section but since I am up late anyway here we go.
<br />

<br />
Cast a darkness line spell on a mob. This will slow its movement rate and make it angry enough to chase you. 
<br />

<br />
The key to kiting is to stay ahead of the mob. You want enough distance between you and it so that you can cast other spells on it before it gets to you. After darkness has landed run away a bit and then cast another spell. Repeat the process until the mob is dead. 
<br />

<br />
Make sure you turn pet taunt off before you send your pet in to beat on the mob. The idea is to make sure you always have aggro so that your pet does not get beat on.
<br />

<br />
Also you want to make sure that you reapply darkness before it wears off so that the mob stays nice and slowed. 
<br />

<br />
Fear kiting works along the same general principle only you want to follow darkness with fear so that the mob runs away from you instead of chasing you. The same rule about recasting darkness before it wears off applies as does gaining more aggro than your pet so that when fear wears off the mob comes walking back towards you instead of tearing your pet a new one. Recast fear as necessary.
<br />

<br />
I prefer fear kiting. In wide open spaces I find it a more efficient way of killing. Kiting lends you more control of the situation as you direct where the mob will go and can steer clear of any danger.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
